<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 94 / International Company News: CIBC earnings rise 20%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce, Canada's second-biggest bank, saw net
profits rise 20 per cent in the second quarter, and 23 per cent in the first
half.
Retail and corporate banking results were strong in the second quarter, said
Mr Al Flood, chairman, and net non-performing loans declined for the fifth
consecutive quarter.
However, the investment banking unit was slowed by volatile markets and
lower trading activity.
CIBC's net profit for the three months ending April 30 was CDollars 217m
(USDollars 156m) or 86 cents a share, against CDollars 180m or 75 cents a
year earlier. The latest period included CDollars 18m from the sale of the
bank's UK mortgage subsidiary.
First-half earnings were CDollars 431m, or CDollars 1.72 a share, compared
with CDollars 349m or CDollars 1.49 a year earlier. Second-quarter return on
assets rose to 0.61 per cent from 0.54 per cent, and on equity to 11.9 per
cent from 10.8 per cent.
Non-interest income was strong. Wood Gundy, the investment banking unit,
could not keep up the pace of the record first quarter, but still registered
an increase on a year earlier. Net interest income rose 4 per cent.
Total assets reached CDollars 147bn, up CDollars 2.6bn.
Net non-performing loans at April 30 were CDollars 1.98bn or 1.9 per cent of
total loans and acceptances, down from 2.9 per cent a year earlier.
Loan loss provisions for fiscal 1994 were unchanged at CDollars 880m, half
of which was charged in the first two quarters. Actual loan loss in fiscal
1993 was CDollars 920m.
</TEXT>
