<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 94 / AIG fund to invest Dollars 1.1bn in Asian projects
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
American International Group, the US insurer, will today announce it has
raised Dollars 1.1bn (Pounds 730m) for investment in infrastructure in
developing Asian countries, about half of it destined for power,
telecommunications and transport projects in China.
The government of Singapore, through two of its investment funds, has
provided Dollars 250m of the money, signalling a policy to switch more of
its international investment to supporting Asian development. The fund is
backed by 24 institutional investors, most of them pension funds and others
based in the US.
The completion of the fund comes just 10 days after Tiger Management, one of
the biggest hedge fund groups, was forced to withdraw its own planned
Dollars 1bn infrastructure fund.
In an attempt to kick-start that fund, Tiger and GE Investments, which
manages pension fund money for General Electric, earlier this year agreed to
contribute Dollars 225m between them. However, the proposed fund is believed
to have suffered from the adverse publicity hedge funds attracted after some
made big losses in financial markets earlier this year.
The fate of the most ambitious infrastructure investment scheme announced to
date, between hedge fund manager Mr George Soros and GE Capital, General
Electric's financial services arm, remains unclear. In January, each side
agreed to contribute Dollars 200m to the venture, which was intended
eventually to attract as much as Dollars 2.5bn to invest in power projects
in developing countries.
Yesterday, GE Capital said that no efforts were under way to attract
additional investors. 'We are focusing our energies right now on finding
investment opportunities. Securing other investors was not the priority,' it
said.
The AIG fund will be managed by Emerging Markets Corporation, a
Washington-based company set up two years ago by two World Bank veterans, Mr
Moeen Qureshi and Mr Don Roth. AIG has put Dollars 100m into the fund. GE,
which has backed infrastructure funds to support the sale of its own power
generation equipment in developing countries, is also believed to be an
investor.
Around half of the Bermuda-registered fund is expected to be invested in
projects in China, with the rest in Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Taiwan and Thailand.
The closed-end fund is believed to have set a target of achieving a 20-25
per cent compound annual return for investors over its projected 10-year
life.
Earlier this year, Mr Qureshi, a former caretaker prime minister of
Pakistan, said that the fund respresented 'a sea change in the willingness
of long-term investors to venture out into developing countries'.
</TEXT>
