<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 94 / Assurance on profit margins at Siebe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Siebe, the international controls and engineering group, yesterday reported
a 20 per cent increase in profitability and sought to allay concern that it
was suffering margin pressure.
The UK-based group increased pre-tax profits from Pounds 182m to Pounds 217m
in the year to April 2, while sales grew by 15 per cent, from Pounds 1.62bn
to Pounds 1.86bn. Currency translation boosted the profits figure by Pounds
13m and sales by Pounds 133m.
Mr Allen Yurko, chief executive, said the group's return on sales had dipped
from 14.7 to 14.3 per cent, but this was attributable to acquisitions made
during the year.
Underlying margins were slightly ahead, although the group was concentrating
on increasing market share, rather than pushing up margins. Mr Yurko said
the group had also adjusted intra-group pricing to take less profits in the
US.
Mr Barrie Stephens, chairman, said the final quarter of the year confirmed
indications of a considerable improvement in certain markets, 'particularly
in North and South America, Asia and, to a limited extent, in the UK and
Australasia'.
He added that although there had been signs of improved demand, Siebe
continued to believe continental European and Japanese markets would remain
subdued until the end of this calendar year, particularly as many customers
relied heavily on domestic demand 'which is at present quiet in these
areas'.
Sales in the controls divisions, after excluding currency translation and
acquisitions, increased by 5.9 per cent and were particularly strong in the
second half. Mr Yurko said he was confident that these divisions would show
real growth of 10 per cent in the current year.
Operating cashflow rose to Pounds 126m from Pounds 95m, and gearing fell
from 66 to 25 per cent. Shareholders' funds rose by Pounds 208m to Pounds
950m, thanks mainly to last November's Pounds 184m rights issue.
The profits figure was struck after Pounds 17.3m of restructuring costs,
down from Pounds 11.4m the previous year.
Earnings per share rose by 19.4 per cent to 31.4p (26.3p). A final dividend
of 7.34p gives a total of 11p (9.86p), an increase of 11.6 per cent.
Lex, Page 18
</TEXT>
