<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Coverage of the First Test against New Zealand at Trent Bridge starts this
morning at 10.55 on BBC1. Afternoon play begins on BBC2 at 1.45, and the
same channel shows highlights at 11.20 pm. There is also ball by ball
commentary on Test Match Special on Radio 4 long wave, which is not the same
without the late Brian Johnston, bless his chocolate cakes. Yet it is still
a unique programme, and aficionados will, as ever, watch television with the
sound turned down and listen to the radio commentary, which begins at 11.00
am. At 8.00 pm BBC1 is repeating an episode from the 1977 series Secret Army
in which Bernard Hepton played the owner of a Belgian restaurant which
served as HQ for the resistance. It was this series more than real events
which gave rise to the comedy 'Allo Allo'. A new gardening series on Channel
4, Over The Garden Wall, looks at the natural conditions in various parts of
Britain and at how wild plants have adapted to them (9.00). The day's best
movie is The Scarlet Empress with Dietrich as Catherine The Great (12.30
BBC2).
