<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 94 / Walker 'driving force' in fraud: Court hears of alleged
thefts totalling Pounds 17m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr George Walker, former chairman and chief executive of Brent Walker, the
property and leisure group, fraudulently inflated the company's profits in
the mid-1980s to mislead investors and creditors about the success and
financial health of his business empire, it was alleged at the Old Bailey
yesterday.
Mr Peter Rook QC, prosecuting for the Serious Fraud Office, told the jury
yesterday that Mr Walker was the 'driving force' behind a fraud which also
involved the theft of Pounds 17m from the company and complex
misrepresentations of the company's accounts to conceal the dishonesty from
the outside world,
Mr Rook was opening the prosecution case on the first day of the trial of Mr
Walker and Mr Wilfred Aquilina, a former Brent Walker group finance
director.
Mr Walker faces four charges of theft involving a total of Pounds 17m, two
charges of false accounting and one of conspiring to falsify the Brent
Walker accounts to overstate the company's profits and assets. Mr Aquilina
faces one charge of the theft of Pounds 4.5m, three charges of false
accounting and one of conspiring to falsify the company's accounts. Both men
deny all the charges.
Mr Rook said the fraud centred on the activities of Brent Walker's film,
television and video subsidiary. Between 1984 and 1987 the profits of this
division were artificially boosted by Pounds 19.3m - profits which also
appeared in the accounts of the overall group which reported healthy results
to shareholders throughout the period.
He said: 'In reality, this income was not true income. The profits were
bogus. They did not reflect proper commercial transactions. Brent Walker was
funding its own profits' He said the profit-boosting, financed from Brent
Walker funds, proved expensive and cost the company Pounds 30m.
The fraud made a substantial difference to the apparent health of Brent
Walker, he said. In 1987 the media division made a Pounds 1.7m loss when in
reality it was claimed the subsidiary was responsible for almost half of
group profits. Had this been known by the markets the subsequent history of
Brent Walker might have been very different.
To keep the illegal profit-boosting concealed, the company accounts had to
be massaged, he said. Mr Walker and Mr Aquilina were aided in this by two
former directors of the media division, Mr Donald Anderson and Mr John
Quested.
Mr Rook said this was done by falsely stating that film rights had been sold
to three purchasers. In all cases, however, the purchasers were refunded
their money by Brent Walker through a series of complex circular
transactions.
To keep the fraud concealed, it became necessary for Mr Walker and Mr
Aquilina to extract even more money from the company and to continue
manipulating the company accounts.
He said: 'Each time the defendants tried to paper over the cracks, cracks
appeared elsewhere so other measures would have to be taken to cover up the
situation.'
The Brent Walker auditors, Leigh Carr, must have been 'less than vigilant',
Mr Rook said. However, when some of the bogus transactions were first
questioned in the press, Mr Walker misled KPMG Peat Marwick, joint auditors
from 1988, and lied to the Stock Exchange.
The trial, expected to last up to five months, continues today.
</TEXT>
