<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 94 / British Chambers of Commerce annual meeting: Ashdown urges
training takeover
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Chambers of commerce should take over the Training and Enterprise Councils
which administer government training schemes in England and Wales, Mr Paddy
Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader, said yesterday.
He urged a greater role for local business in determining not only the
pattern of education and training but also of local infrastructure
investment.
He also argued for chambers of commerce to be given a statutory role, as
they have in Germany - a suggestion advocated by Mr Michael Heseltine, the
trade and industry secretary, when he was out of office.
Mr Ashdown said companies would have to belong to the local chamber and in
return they would have the benefit of a single voice when speaking to
government and a single framework for training. The chambers, he said,
'should take on responsibilities for the Tecs themselves'.
There are 82 employer-led Tecs in England and Wales, which have increasingly
taken a role in local economic development as well as training since their
creation just more than three years ago.
Mr Ashdown also said the Liberal Democrats would legislate to make interest
payable on overdue debt, a step which the government rejected in its white
paper on competitiveness.
But he made his strongest comments as part of an advocation for a stronger
voice for the UK in the European Union. This is a subject about which
smaller companies have a distinctly cool view, a sur-vey by the British
Chambers of Commerce found yester-day.
The survey of 364 small companies found 72 per cent opposed to the EU
becoming responsible for wider areas of policy.
But 60 per cent of the companies said they had not been affected by the
single European market and slightly more did not know the name of their
member of the European parliament.
More than half of them claimed to have had no benefits from the single
market.
</TEXT>
