<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 94 / British Chambers of Commerce annual meeting: Cadbury urges
new roles for companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Boards of UK companies will have to give greater recognition to their
responsibilities towards employees and society, Sir Adrian Cadbury, the
chairman of the committee on corporate governance, warned yesterday.
He presented this as part of a process which would bring about some
convergence between British and continental European practice.
Underlying his remarks was the thought that the form of company boards will
change, given UK membership of the European Union. Sir Adrian said the UK
viewed a company as a capitalist enterprise, while the Continent saw it as a
coalition of interests and a partnership between capital and labour.
Sir Adrian said that if there was to be a convergence between these two
notions British boards would have to recognise a wider responsibility while
Continental companies would have to pay 'more regard to shareholders' rights
and Anglo-American standards of disclosure, especially if they want to tap
international sources of equity finance'.
</TEXT>
