<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 94 / McAlpine attacks Major's campaign
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major's handling of the European election campaign was bitterly
attacked yesterday by Lord McAlpine, who was Conservative party treasurer
during Baroness Thatcher's premiership.
However, Mr Major's concept of a multi-speed Europe was given full backing
by Mr Michael Heseltine, a leading cabinet member of the Tory pro-European
wing.
Lord McAlpine, writing in The European newspaper, said Mr Major's criticism
of beggars would go down as a 'minor classic in the annals of political
nastiness'. The comments had been made to win votes, not because they were
sincerely believed.
'This is a form of politics that I detest,' he said. 'I consider myself to
be on the rightwing of British politics. These words uttered by a
Conservative leader fill me with shame at being a Conservative.'
Mr Heseltine said his view of the future of the European Union was 'exactly
the same' as that spelt out by Mr Major: 'You can be at the heart of Europe
 -and we should be at the heart of Europe - but the outcome of negotiations
can be multi-tiered and multi-speed.'
Mr Heseltine said the opposition parties were prepared to 'sign up to almost
any idea called Europe without checking the details'. He added: 'We believe
it is worth having a hassle over the details before you sign up to the
principle.'
His comments suggest that the party's pro-Europeans are likely to cloak
their distaste for the prime minister's Euro-sceptic rhetoric - intended to
encourage core Conservative supporters to vote - until after polling day on
Thursday.
Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, told businessmen in Birmingham that the
government was seeking a 'decentralised, de-regulating and competitive
Europe'.
</TEXT>
