<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 94 / House price fall triggers Halifax warning on rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Halifax Building Society, Britain's largest mortgage lender, yesterday
reported the biggest monthly fall in house prices for 12 months and warned
the government not to damage the fragile housing market by raising interest
rates.
Halifax said UK house prices fell on average by 1.6 per cent during May,
compared with the previous month. It is the second month in succession that
the society has reported a price fall. In April, prices fell 0.3 per cent.
Mr John Wriglesworth, housing analyst with stockbroker UBS, said yesterday
he was halving his forecast for house price increases in 1994 from 7 per
cent to 3.5 per cent after the Halifax survey. 'This is a serious wobble on
the road to recovery,' said Mr Wriglesworth.
Halifax, which previously had forecast that house prices would rise on
average by 5 per cent this year, says it now expects smaller increases,
possibly of 2-3 per cent.
Tax increases which took effect in April and a rush to complete purchases
ahead of the ending of fixed price mortgages which caused a bunching of
sales earlier this year, were the most likely causes for the decline, it
said. The latest falls mean the average price of a home of Pounds 62,728 has
remained static over the previous 12 months. It is the first time since
August 1993 that the Halifax has not reported a year-on-year price rise.
Only three months ago, in February, Halifax reported a year-on-year increase
of 3.8 per cent, the highest annual increase since November 1989.
In a clear warning to the government, it said concern that inflation might
be returning, particularly asset price inflation, had been 'greatly
overblown'.
'Any moves to raise interest rates, tighten fiscal policy or mount a further
attack on housing market subsidies would risk destroying a very fragile
recovery.'
Signals from the housing market, however, remain mixed. Average prices for
new homes, for example, rose by 0.6 per cent last month, according to
Halifax.
Housebuilders, are estimated to have increased sales by 10-15 per cent
during the first five months of this year.
Halifax's latest survey also conflicts with a study by Nationwide, the
country's second largest building society, which reported on Wednesday that
house prices had risen by 1.4 per cent in May compared with the previous
month.
Mr Brian Davis, Nationwide's operations director, warned: 'Recent indicators
of market activity have been mixed. The underlying strengthening of the
market which began in the spring of last year is likely to be maintained but
progress is steady rather than spectacular.'
The Council of Mortgage Lenders said the revised 1994 forecast for house
prices by Halifax was in line with its own assessment of the market.
Mr Wriglesworth, in spite of reducing his 1994 forecast, believed the market
would bounce back this month. Houses were the most affordable for many
years, and mortgage interest rates low, he said.
