<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 94 / VAT rebate claims for hospitality under threat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Over-enthusiastic claims by companies for rebates of value added tax on
business entertainment expenses yesterday prompted HM Custom &amp; Excise to
threaten a clampdown on corporate hospitality.
Custom &amp; Excise believes that goods or services bought for the purpose of
business entertainment should not be eligible for VAT refunds, even if they
are also partly used for other more serious and sober business activities.
European and English law has long prevented VAT relief on pure business
hospitality, but it has left a grey area when it comes to other business
activities which include an element of entertainment.
In the light of a series of contradictory VAT tribunal and court judgments,
Customs said yesterday it would put all appeals on entertainment-related
cases on hold while seeking guidance from the courts.
The problem started with Plant and Repair (South Wales), a small
Cardiff-based company, which tried to claim back as office expenses some of
the VAT on its costs for maintaining a box at Cardiff Arms Park, the Welsh
national rugby stadium.
The company insisted it used the box primarily as an office and only
incidentally for entertaining clients at the weekend. The VAT tribunal was
unconvinced and forbade any rebate.
It took the same sceptical view of a rebate claim from Thorn-EMI, which
asked for its VAT back on some of the costs of running its hospitality
chalet at the Farnborough Airshow.
But the High Court upheld the company's claim in March, arguing that its
chalets were temporary offices and that it was possible to apportion its
expenses between business and entertainment costs.
Customs said yesterday it would take the case to the court of appeal, while
conceding in the meantime that companies may claim back VAT on their
non-entertainment costs. It also said it would consult companies to assess
their views.
Mr Andrew Ball, a tax partner with accountants Touche Ross, said: 'It is
extraordinary that Customs is appealing.'
He added that he did not believe most companies offering corporate
hospitality at events such as Wimbledon or Glyndebourne even attempted to
claim VAT rebates. Those affected were more likely businesses attending
trade fairs.
Whatever the ultimate finding, it will have little impact on Plant and
Repair and its box at Cardiff Arms Park. The company has since gone into
liquidation.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
