<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow recovers initial fall on
inflation fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
Blue chip stocks finished with modest gains yesterday after recovering from
early declines touched off by inflationary jitters in the bond market,
writes Frank McGurty in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was 2.46 higher at 3,760.83,
while the more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 gained 1.13 at 457.63.
Volume on the New York SE was moderate, with 278.5m shares changing hands.
In the secondary markets, the American SE composite shed 0.57 to 439.88 but
the Nasdaq composite added 0.33 at 735.52.
For most of the session, stocks moved in step with the US Treasury market.
Its first move was down sharply. At mid-morning, bonds went into a tailspin
when the National Association of Purchasing Management released the results
of its monthly survey.
The closely watched report actually offered a mixed view of the economy. Its
overall May index was unchanged from the previous month, but the prices
index showed a big rise from April. The data suggested that a gradual
escalation of demand for raw materials had begun to feed through to prices
paid by manufacturers. The trend, reasoned inflation-sensitive bond traders,
would soon lead to higher prices paid by consumers.
But government securities managed to stabilise and gradually retrace all the
ground lost immediately after the NAPM's announcement. Sliding prices for
gold and other commodities helped to soothe nerves, as did talk of outright
bond purchases by the Federal Reserve, a move which carried no policy
implications.
During the afternoon, bonds continued to move ahead, ending the day with
solid gains. The gradual improvement in the Treasury market helped the Dow
industrials to a point. After falling by as many as 25 points during the
morning, the bellwether index could only manage to nudge slightly into the
plus column.
A few cyclical stocks were stubbornly anchored in negative territory.
Caterpillar lost Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 105 1/2 and Cummins slipped
Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 42 1/4 . But Chevron, up Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 88
1/4 , Sears Roebuck, Dollars 1 1/4 higher at Dollars 51 7/8 , and
International Paper, Dollars 1 3/4 ahead at Dollars 71, rallied during the
afternoon.
Banking issues also pushed higher in late trading. Bankers Trust gained
Dollars 1 7/8 at Dollars 72 1/4 , Chase Manhattan added Dollars 1 5/8 at
Dollars 39 3/8 and Chemical Bank ended Dollars 1 3/8 better at Dollars 39
3/4 . Analysts said the gains may reflect a shift away from cyclical issues
in response to the recent evidence of a cooling economy.
Takeover speculation in the pharmaceuticals field emerged once again. This
time the potential target was US Surgical, the medical equipment supplier.
The stock jumped Dollars 2 1/2 to Dollars 21 1/2 on expectations that
Ciba-Geigy, the Swiss drug group, would launch a takeover bid.
International Game Technology improved Dollars 1 to Dollars 23 1/8 . Its
management issued a positive assessment of the company's prospects in an
effort to arrest the recent slide in its share price.
Canada
Toronto tumbled in moderate trade, dragged down by a dropping gold price and
weak Canadian bonds. The TSE 300 index fell 37.1 to close at 4,289.7 and
declines led rises by 466 to 288 in volume of 56.2m shares.
Canadian bond markets felt the impact of heavy foreign selling of Quebec
bonds due to nervousness over forthcoming elections in the province.
Bond prices recovered somewhat but the TSE 300 index managed only a slight
rally from its intraday low.
Brazil
After opening easier following disappointment over the failure by a
congressional committee to agree a revision of the constitution late on
Tuesday, the Bovespa index picked up again. By the close the index stood a
net 593, or 2.4 per cent, higher at 25,265.
Brokers said liquidity had risen by late morning as foreign investors
returned to the market. The day's turnover reached Cr348.6bn (Dollars
182.7m).
An announcement shortly after the market closed by Mr Rubens Ricupero, the
economy minister, of new rules for Brazil's new currency, the real, to be
introduced on July 1, was seen as providing support for Friday's opening.
Brazilian markets are closed today due to the Corpus Christi holiday.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
