FT  02 JUN 94 / International Company News: Workers seek to stop USAir
contract move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Labour unions at USAir, the US carrier in which British Airways holds a 22
per cent stake, say they are seeking a federal injunction to stop the
airline's plans to contract out its airfreight and mail handling operations
at 35 cities, writes Richard Tomkins in New York.
USAir announced the move last week, saying it would save Dollars 10m a year.
The 510 full-time and 122 part-time workers affected would be invited to
apply for other jobs within the company, it said.
Just before USAir announced the move, a majority of its 8,000 fleet service
workers had voted to join a union.
Yesterday, the United Steelworkers of America, one of the unions covering
the industry, accused USAir of trying to discourage employees from joining
by creating the impression it would retaliate with lay-offs.
USAir said the union's suit was 'baseless and without merit'.
