<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 94 / Observer: Shaggy tail
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Eugene Rotberg, former treasurer of the World Bank, has a tall tale
concerning a banker, a corporate treasurer and a dog.
The banker and treasurer perambulate past a pet shop window and spy a dog
for sale. The banker buys it for Dollars 5, then sells it to the treasurer
for Dollars 10. A few days later, the banker wants it back, so he bids
Dollars 20. The dog keeps changing hands until the banker buys it for
Dollars 1m.
Then the dog escapes from the bank and is killed by a car. The treasurer is
furious: 'Couldn't you have been more careful?' he complains to the banker.
'Don't you realise how much money we were making on that dog?'
