<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
According to today's edition of The Business, bullying is not limited to
school playgrounds but is commonplace in industry and commerce. One 'stress
expert' says that if enough employees are bullied it can put a company out
of business. It seems that one senior manager at Ford was so demoralised by
his new bosses that he left, brought a case of constructive dismissal, and
won a large settlement (7.30 BBC2). This week's episode in Jack Rosenthal's
drama about removal men, Moving Story, lasts 60 minutes which must surely
mean an improvement on last week's 90-minute episode. As we have come to
expect from Rosenthal, the quality is largely in the characters and the
opening story was over-stretched (9.00 ITV). The outrage from some medical
people at the portrait of hospital life in Cardiac Arrest must stem either
from blindness or from the same rage that affected Caliban upon looking in
the mirror. In the last episode of the opening series (9.35 BBC1) life and
death decisions are being taken on the hoof, as ever, and some of the staff
are behaving badly.
